what does this command do: ssh -i "~/UserKey.pem" -C -L 25900:localhost:5900 user@ec2-34-221-131-108.us-west-2.compute.amazonaws.com
This command sets up an SSH tunnel from the local machine to a remote server, allowing for port forwarding between the two machines. Specifically, it uses the "ssh" command with the "-i" option to specify the location of a private key file ("~/UserKey.pem"), and the "-C" option to prevent echoing of commands in the terminal window. The "-L" option is used to set up a local port forwarding from port 25900 on the local machine to port 5900 on the remote server, with "user@ec2-34-221-131-108.us-west-2.compute.amazonaws.com" specifying the IP address and username of the remote server.
